  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering policies\n- Provides guidelines for international financial institutions\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets international banking standards for preventing money laundering\n\n4. Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing and cooperation\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Set specific regulations for EU member states\n\nMost countries have national laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Conduct customer due diligence\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal control systems\n\nWhile these laws exist, enforcement and effectiveness can vary between jurisdictions.",
